{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ead221fa-7104-468d-bd66-1068c29bba51","content":"With Microsoft.Testing.Platform, VSTest-style flags move after `--` and use new names. You'll also need to add NuGet packages for each extension.\n\n**New command:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- \\\n  --treenode-filter \"/*[Category=Integration]\" \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --collect-coverage \\\n  --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump \\\n  --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\n**Required NuGet packages** (add to your test project):\n\n| Extension | Package |\n|---|---|\n| TRX logging | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` |\n| Code coverage | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage` |\n| Crash dump | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump` |\n| Hang dump | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump` |\n\n**Key differences:**\n- Platform args go after `--`\n- `--filter` → `--treenode-filter` with XPath-like syntax (`/*[Category=Integration]`)\n- `--logger trx` → `--report-trx`\n- `--collect \"Code Coverage\"` → `--collect-coverage` + `--coverage-output-format cobertura`\n- `--blame-crash` → `--crashdump`\n- `--blame-hang` / `--blame-hang-timeout` → `--hangdump` / `--hangdump-timeout`","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"60d34d9d-3f9c-45d0-95e5-8fe00ae27a5c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating a `dotnet test` command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing infrastructure, not a codebase task. Let me provide the answer directly.\n\nKey differences when moving to Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n\n1. `--filter` → `--filter` (same, but the flag is supported)\n2. `--logger trx` → `--report-trx` \n3. `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` → `--collect-coverage` with Microsoft.CodeCoverage, or you need to configure it differently\n\n\n4. `--blame-crash` → `--crashdump`\n5. `--blame-hang` → `--hangdump`\n6. `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` → `--hangdump-timeout 5m`\n\nThough I need to be more precise here. With Microsoft.Testing.Platform, the test executable becomes the entry point, and while `dotnet test` still works as a wrapper, the flag syntax differs depending on whether you're using `dotnet test` or running the executable directly. When using `dotnet test`, flags get passed through with `--`, but the direct executable approach uses different flag names entirely.\n\nFor Microsoft.Testing.Platform via `dotnet test`, the mappings are: `--filter` remains unchanged, `--logger trx` becomes `--report-trx` (needs Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport), `--collect \"Code Coverage\"` becomes `--collect-coverage` (needs Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage), and the blame options map to `--crashdump`, `--hangdump`, and `--hangdump-timeout` respectively (each requiring their corresponding extension). When invoking through `dotnet test`, you pass these Microsoft.Testing.Platform options after `--`.\n\nActually, I need to reconsider the filter behavior—with Microsoft.Testing.Platform, filtering works differently than VSTest. The `--treenode-filter` option is the primary filtering mechanism, though there may be backward compatibility support for `--filter` depending on the MSTest adapter version. Let me think through what the actual command syntax should look like here. I'm mapping out the specific command-line arguments for each feature—TRX reporting, code coverage with Cobertura format, crash dumps, and hang dumps with timeout—along with their required NuGet packages. These mappings feel solid, so I can give a confident answer now.","outputTokens":1425},"id":"1290ae04-9e69-4a93-8e8e-82e3153c2389","timestamp":"2026-04-07T15:55:47.133Z","parentId":"3390f667-d09d-4460-81d5-fe936b3d5797"}
